.TH LUAI 1 "June 2026" "luainstaller v1.0.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
luai, luainstaller \- analyze and package Lua projects into same-environment executables

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B luai
.BR a " " \fIentry.lua\fR
.RI [ options ]
.br
.B luai
.BR t " " \fIentry.lua\fR
.RI [ options ]
.br
.B luai
.BR b " " \fIentry.lua\fR
.RI [ options ]
.br
.B luai
.BR \-\-version

.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBluainstaller\fR is a tool that analyzes Lua dependencies and packages Lua projects into
\fBsame-environment executables\fR. The current verified sample matrix covers Linux,
macOS, and Windows \fB--onedir\fR and \fB--onefile\fR output through local and lab
scripts. It is open-sourced on GitHub and licensed under the
\fBLGPL\fR. See the repository for source code, releases, and documentation:
https://github.com/Water-Run/luainstaller

\fBluainstaller\fR provides dependency analysis and same-platform directory bundling capabilities, and can
package non-pure-Lua content inside the wrapper program. It is important to note that
\fBluainstaller\fR guarantees that the packaged binary will run on the same \fBsystem environment\fR
as yours. The verified Linux, macOS, and Windows bundles do not require a separate
\fBlua\fR command, but system ABI and native library compatibility still matter.

\fBluainstaller\fR can be used as a CLI tool and (when installed via LuaRocks) as a Lua module via
\fBrequire("luainstaller")\fR.

.SH INSTALLATION
Install via LuaRocks:
.nf
luarocks install luainstaller
.fi
This installs the \fBluai\fR and \fBluainstaller\fR CLI commands, the Lua module,
and \fBluai(1)\fR / \fBluainstaller(1)\fR man pages.
.PP
Install from a source checkout when LuaRocks is unavailable:
.nf
sh tools/install-source.sh --prefix "$HOME/.local"
export PATH="$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH"
luai --help
luainstaller -v
.fi
The source installer only requires a \fBlua\fR command. Building \fB--onedir\fR or \fB--onefile\fR bundles
still requires the local C toolchain and Lua development metadata. Linux uses \fBcc\fR,
Lua headers, and Lua \fBpkg-config\fR data. macOS uses \fBcc\fR plus a matching Lua
prefix that provides Lua headers and \fBliblua.a\fR. Windows uses MinGW on a Linux
build host plus a Windows Lua prefix that provides Lua headers and \fBlua54.dll\fR.

.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B a
Analyze Lua and native module dependencies.
.TP
.B t
Print trace records for dependency resolution decisions and compatibility diagnostics.
.TP
.B b
Build an onedir bundle or self-extracting onefile bundle.
.PP
Compatibility aliases are kept for existing scripts: \fB-a\fR/\fBanalyze\fR,
\fB-t\fR/\fBtrace\fR, and \fB-c\fR/\fBbuild\fR.

.SH CLI USAGE
The CLI tool names are \fBluai\fR and \fBluainstaller\fR.

.SS Help
.nf
luai --help
luainstaller -v
.fi
Typical output:
.nf
luai / luainstaller - Package Lua projects into same-environment executables

Usage:
  luai a <entry.lua> [options]
  luai t <entry.lua> [options]
  luai b <entry.lua> [options]

Options:
  ...
.fi

.SS Bundle

Onedir mode:
.nf
luai b --dir \fIentry.lua\fR -o \fIoutput_dir\fR
.fi
Typical output:
.nf
success.
\fIoutput_dir\fR/\fIapp\fR
.fi

\fBluai\fR performs static dependency analysis starting from the entry \fB.lua\fR file, embeds
Lua sources in a generated launcher, copies the linked Lua shared runtime and detected native
Lua C modules into \fB.luai/native/\fR, and writes \fB.luai/manifest.lua\fR.

Single-file mode:
.nf
luai b --file \fIentry.lua\fR -o \fIoutput_executable\fR
.fi
The generated executable extracts an inner onedir layout to a content-addressed
cache directory, then starts the inner launcher.

.SS analyze
Analyze dependencies only:
.nf
luai a \fIentry.lua\fR
.fi
Typical output:
.nf
success.
\fIentry.lua\fR
N script(s), M library(ies)
.fi

.SS trace
Trace dependency resolution and compatibility boundaries:
.nf
luai t \fIentry.lua\fR
.fi
Typical output includes analyzer records followed by a \fBcompatibility\fR section
that states the same OS, same architecture, same ABI, and same Lua ABI promise.

.SH OPTIONS
The following options apply to \fBa\fR, \fBt\fR, and/or \fBb\fR as described.

.TP
.BI \-o ", " \-\-out " " path
Output path.
For \fBb --dir\fR: a directory path.
Examples:
.nf
luai b main.lua --out ../dist/app
.fi

.TP
.B \-\-dir ", " \-\-onedir
Generate a Linux, macOS, or Windows directory bundle. This is the default bundle mode.

.TP
.B \-\-file ", " \-\-onefile
Generate a self-extracting single-file executable.

.TP
.BI \-\-target\-os " " os
Select the target profile. Supported values are \fBlinux\fR, \fBmacos\fR, and
\fBwindows\fR. If omitted, the host OS is used.

.TP
.BI \-\-lua\-prefix " " path
Lua prefix used by targets that need explicit headers or runtime files. macOS
expects \fBinclude/lua.h\fR and \fBlib/liblua.a\fR. Windows expects
\fBinclude/lua.h\fR and \fBbin/lua54.dll\fR or \fBlua54.dll\fR.

.TP
.BI \-v ", " \-\-verbose
Enable verbose analysis and bundling logs.
.nf
luai b main.lua --verbose
.fi

.TP
.BI \-\-max\-deps " " n
Maximum number of dependencies allowed (default: 36).
.nf
luai b main.lua --max-deps 100
luai a main.lua --max-deps 50
.fi

.TP
.BI \-\-include " " path
Manually include additional dependencies. May be specified multiple times.
Use this for dynamic \fBrequire\fR patterns that static analysis cannot detect.
.nf
luai b main.lua --include ./require.lua --include ./plugin.lua
.fi

.TP
.BI \-\-exclude " " path
Manually exclude dependencies. May be specified multiple times.
Use this to remove false positives (for example, \fBpcall(require, ...)\fR patterns); takes priority
over \fB--include\fR.
.nf
luai b main.lua --exclude ./test_utils.lua
.fi

.TP
.B \-\-no\-depscan
Disable dependency scanning. This is a compatibility alias for
\fB--require-engine manual\fR, where you must specify all
dependencies via \fB--include\fR.
.nf
luai b main.lua --no-depscan --include ./a.lua --include ./b.lua
.fi

.TP
.BI \-r ", " \-\-require\-engine " " engine
Select dependency discovery. Supported values are \fBstatic\fR, \fBmanual\fR, and
\fBruntime\fR. \fBstatic\fR is the default analyzer. \fBmanual\fR uses only explicit
\fB--include\fR inputs. \fBruntime\fR runs the entry script once while tracing
actual \fBrequire\fR calls; arguments after \fB--\fR are passed to that build-time
run.
.nf
luai b --file main.lua -r runtime -- seed --verbose
.fi

.SH LUA API
When installed via LuaRocks, \fBluainstaller\fR can be invoked from Lua. The Lua API uses the same
parameter semantics as the CLI. Dependency scanning is enabled by default; set
\fBdepscan = false\fR to disable it.

.nf
local luainstaller = require("luainstaller")
.fi

.SS bundle
Structured result:
.nf
local result = luainstaller.bundle({
  entry = "main.lua",
  mode = "onedir",
  out = "dist/app",
})
.fi
When \fBresult.ok=true\fR, \fBresult.executable\fR is the generated launcher path and
\fBresult.manifest\fR is the manifest table. Normal user errors return
\fB{ ok = false, error = { type = "...", message = "..." } }\fR.

Parameters (\fIopts\fR table):

.TS
lB lB lB lB
l l l l.
Parameter	Type	Default	Description
_
\fBentry\fR	string	required	Entry script path
\fBmode\fR	string	\fBonedir\fR	Bundle mode: \fBonedir\fR or \fBonefile\fR
\fBout\fR	string	\-	Output directory for \fBonedir\fR; executable path for \fBonefile\fR
\fBtarget_os\fR	string	host OS	Target profile: \fBlinux\fR, \fBmacos\fR, or \fBwindows\fR
\fBlua_prefix\fR	string	\fBLUAI_LUA_PREFIX\fR	Lua headers/runtime prefix for macOS and Windows
\fBverbose\fR	boolean	\fBfalse\fR	Whether to output detailed logs
\fBmax_deps\fR	number	\fB36\fR	Maximum number of dependencies
\fBinclude\fR	string[]	\fB{}\fR	Manually include dependencies
\fBexclude\fR	string[]	\fB{}\fR	Manually exclude dependencies (priority over \fBinclude\fR)
\fBdepscan\fR	boolean	\fBtrue\fR	Enable automatic dependency analysis
\fBrequire_engine\fR	string	\fBstatic\fR	Dependency engine: \fBstatic\fR, \fBmanual\fR, or \fBruntime\fR
\fBrun_args\fR	string[]	\fB{}\fR	Arguments for \fBruntime\fR require discovery
.TE

Example:
.nf
local result = luainstaller.bundle({ entry = "main.lua", out = "../dist/app" })
if result.ok then
  print("Bundle succeeded: " .. result.executable)
else
  print("Bundle failed: " .. result.error.message)
end
.fi

.SS analyze
Structured result:
.nf
local result = luainstaller.analyze({ entry = "main.lua" })
.fi
When \fBresult.ok=true\fR, \fBresult.dependencies.scripts\fR and
\fBresult.dependencies.libraries\fR contain discovered files.

Parameters:

.TS
lB lB lB lB
l l l l.
Parameter	Type	Default	Description
_
\fBentry\fR	string	required	Entry script path
\fBmax_deps\fR	number	\fB36\fR	Maximum number of dependencies
\fBdepscan\fR	boolean	\fBtrue\fR	Enable automatic dependency analysis
.TE

Example:
.nf
local result = luainstaller.analyze({ entry = "main.lua" })
if result.ok then
  print("Found " .. #result.dependencies.scripts .. " Lua dependencies")
else
  print("Analysis failed: " .. result.error.message)
end
.fi

.SH HOW IT WORKS
The workflow of \fBluainstaller\fR can be summarized as: \fBanalyze entry script\fR \->
\fBcollect dependencies\fR \-> \fBtrace resolution decisions\fR \-> \fBbuild a same-platform onedir
or onefile bundle\fR.

When \fBbundle\fR is executed, \fBluainstaller\fR first performs \fBstatic dependency analysis\fR
starting from the entry \fB.lua\fR file. It scans the source code for common reference patterns
such as \fBrequire(...)\fR, recursively finding all Lua files the project depends on. For cases
that static analysis cannot fully cover \(em such as runtime module name concatenation or
conditional module loading \(em dependencies can be supplemented manually via \fB--include\fR and
false positives can be removed via \fB--exclude\fR.

Once the dependency set is determined, the onedir bundler generates C source containing
the Lua bootstrap and embedded Lua payload, compiles it with the local toolchain,
copies detected native Lua C modules into \fB.luai/native/\fR, and writes
\fB.luai/manifest.lua\fR. Linux uses a shared-Lua launcher and copies the linked Lua
shared runtime; macOS links against a static \fBliblua.a\fR from the selected Lua prefix.
Windows uses \fBx86_64-w64-mingw32-gcc\fR, emits a \fB.exe\fR, and copies
\fBlua54.dll\fR beside the launcher and into \fB.luai/native/\fR.

For \fB--onefile\fR, \fBluainstaller\fR first stages that same onedir layout, embeds
the staged files in a native extractor, and writes them to a content-addressed
cache directory at runtime before launching the inner executable. Matching
previously extracted files are reused when their size and content hash match.

The first-stage compatibility promise is same OS, same architecture, same ABI, and same Lua
ABI. The current implementation does not claim cross-platform output, automatic external
shared-library closure, or complete dynamic-require proof. Runtime require discovery only
covers code paths that execute during the build-time trace run.

